<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-factoring-quadratic-trinomials" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Factoring Quadratic Trinomials</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <em>Factoring quadratic trinomials</em> is arguably the single most used skill in high-school mathematics, being used in uncountably many high-school (and college) math problems. In this way, it is a very important foundational skill to master. However, unfortunately, it is among the least important and least useful topics ``in the real world".
    </p>
    <p>
      The goal is to factor any expression of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a, b, c</m> are any integers.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        First, we'll start with a simpler case, when <m>a = 1</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        Then, we'll consider the more difficult case, when <m>a \neq 1</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </introduction>
  
  <subsection xml:id="factoring-x-squared-sum-product">
    <title>Factoring <m>x^2+bx+c</m> (Sum and Product Method)</title>
    <p>
      We want to take an expression like <m>x^2 + 7x + 6</m>, and rewrite it as <m>(x + \quad)(x + \quad)</m>. The question is: how to choose the two numbers to put in the brackets? Observe the pattern for how expansions work. For example, consider the expansion of <m>(x+3)(x+5)</m>,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+3)(x+5) \amp = x^2 + 3x + 5x + 15</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = x^2 + 8x + 15</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      Here are some other expansions,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+2)(x+3) \amp = x^2 + 5x + 6</mrow>
      <mrow>(x+7)(x-2) \amp = x^2 + 5x - 14</mrow>
      <mrow>(x-5)(x-3) \amp = x^2 - 8x + 15</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      Observe how expanding the left side leads to the right side. 
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        On the right side, there are always 3 terms: <m>x^2</m>, an <m>x</m> term, and a constant number term. 
      </li>
      <li>
        To get the coefficient of the middle <m>x</m> term, you <em>add</em> the two numbers in the brackets.
      </li>
      <li>
        To get the last constant term, you <em>multiply</em> those two numbers.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      In other words,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+3)(x+5) \amp = x^2 + 3x + 5x + 15</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = x^2 + \brac{\text{sum of 3 and 5}}x + \brac{\text{product of 3 and 5}}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = x^2 + 8x + 15</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      In general, if we multiply two factors together, say <m>x+a</m> and <m>x+b</m>, we get,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+a)(x+b) \amp = x^2 + ax + bx + ab</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp = x^2 + (a + b)x + ab</mrow>
    </md>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The first term is always <m>x^2</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        The coefficient of the middle term is the <em>sum</em> of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
        The last term is the <em>product</em> of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      In summary,
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \boxed{(x + a)(x + b)
          = x^2
          + \underbrace{(a + b)}_{\substack{\text{coefficient of }x\\\text{is the sum }a + b}}\,x
          + \underbrace{ab}_{\substack{\text{constant term}\\\text{is the product }ab}}}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This leads to a general rule for factoring an expression of the form <m>x^2 + bx + c</m>.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \boxed{\text{To factor }x^2+bx+c\text{, find two numbers that multiply to }c\text{ and add to }b}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      <example>
        <title>Factoring <m>x^2 + 7x + 12</m></title>
        <p>
          Consider,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>x^2 + 7x + 12</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          We want two numbers that multiply to 12 and add to 7. There are many pairs of numbers that add to 7, so we'll start with numbers that multiply to 12. Our choices are:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp 1 \times 12</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp 2 \times 6</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp 3 \times 4</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Notice that if we choose 3 and 4, they also add to 7. So this is the correct combination. Then,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>x^2 + 7x + 12 \amp = (x+3)(x+4)</mrow>
        </md>
      </example>
      <example>
        <title>Factoring With Negative Numbers</title>
        <p>
          Consider,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>x^2 - 5x + 6</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          We want two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to <m>-5</m>. Here are the possible pairs of factors:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp 1 \times 6 \text{ which adds to } 7</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp 2 \times 3 \text{ adds to } 5</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          At first, it seems none of these add to <m>-5</m>. However, we can also have both of our numbers be negative, because two negative numbers also multiply to a positive. For example,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp -1 \times -6 \text{ adds to } -7</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp -2 \times -3 \text{ adds to } -5</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Then, <m>-2</m> and <m>-3</m> is the correct combination. Then,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>x^2 - 5x + 6 = (x-2)(x-3)</mrow>
        </md>
      </example>
      <example>
        <title>Writing in Standard Form</title>
        <p>
          Consider,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>-8x + 12 + x^2</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          This is still a quadratic trinomial. At first glance, it's a bit different than the previous examples, because it's not written in the usual order for a quadratic. The highest power term, <m>x^2</m>, is at the end instead of the beginning.
        </p>
        <p>
          When factoring, you should always arrange the terms in the same order: <m>x^2</m> first, <m>x</m> next, and constant last. This is called <em>descending</em> power order (the exponent on <m>x</m> from largest to smallest), and is often called <em>standard form</em>.
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp -8x + 12 + x^2</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = x^2 - 8x + 12</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Now, it looks like a regular quadratic. We need two numbers that multiply to 12 and add to <m>-8</m>. After some guessing, the correct combination is <m>-2</m> and <m>-6</m>. Therefore,
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp = (x-2)(x-6)</mrow>
        </md>
      </example>
      <p>
        In summary,
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          (If necessary) Arrange the trinomial in descending power order.
        </li>
        <li>
          Find two numbers that multiply to <m>c</m> (the last number), and check if they add to <m>b</m> (the middle number).
        </li>
        <li>
          If they do, then it factors as <m>(x+ \quad)(x + \quad)</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <project>
        <title>Practice Factoring Quadratics 1</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>Factor each quadratic expression.</p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 + 3x + 2</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x+1)(x+2)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - 6x + 8</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-2)(x-4)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 + 7x + 10</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x+5)(x+2)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - 13x + 12</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-1)(x-12)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - 3x - 18</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-6)(x+3)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 + 11x + 18</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x+2)(x+9)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - 2x - 15</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-5)(x+3)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 + x - 6</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x+3)(x-2)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 + 10x + 24</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x+4)(x+6)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - x - 2</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-2)(x+1)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - x - 30</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-6)(x+5)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - x - 6</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-3)(x+2)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p><m>x^2 - 10x + 24</m></p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>(x-4)(x-6)</m></p>
          </answer>
        </task>
      </project>
      <p>
        Some additional helpful observations,
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
          When the constant term <m>c</m> is positive, then the factors of <m>c</m> must be either both positive or both negative.
        </p><ul>
          <li>
            If the middle term <m>b</m> is positive, then both must be positive. E.g. <m>x^2+7x+12 = (x+4)(x+3)</m> (last term is positive, middle term is positive, so both factors are positive)
          </li>
          <li>
            If the middle term is negative, then both must be negative. E.g. <m>x^2-9x+20 = (x-5)(x-4)</m> (last term is positive, middle term is negative, so both factors are negative)
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><p>
        When the constant term <m>c</m> is negative, then the factors of <m>c</m> must have opposite signs (one positive, one negative). The sign of the larger number will be the sign of the coefficient of the middle term.
      </p><ul>
        <li>
          E.g. <m>x^2-x-6=(x-3)(x+2)</m> (last term is negative, so signs are opposite, and middle term is negative, so <m>6 = 3 \times 2</m> and 3 is negative)
        </li>
        <li>
          E.g. <m>x^2+2x-15 = (x+5)(x-3)</m> (last term is negative, so signs are opposite, and middle term is positive, so <m>15 = 5 \times 3</m> and the 5 is positive)
        </li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <example>
    <title>Trinomial That Cannot Be Factored</title>
    <p>
      In fact, not all trinomials can be factored. Consider <m>x^2 + 4x + 6</m>. To factor this, we would need two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 4. The options are: <m>1 \times 6</m> or <m>2 \times 3</m>. Neither of them work. This means that <m>x^2+4x+6</m> is not factorable.
    </p>
  </example>
  <p>
    Polynomials which cannot be factored are called <term>prime</term>, or <term>irreducible</term>. Prime in the same way as a prime number like 7 cannot be factored into smaller pieces, and irreducible similarly means <q>not reducible</q>. For now, problems will almost always have only factorable polynomials.
  </p>
